===Etymology===
First attested in this form around 1620 (referring to a [[bedbug]]), from earlier {{m|en|bugge||beetle}}, a conflation of two words:
# {{der|en|enm|bugge||scarecrow, hobgoblin}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*bugja-||swollen up, thick}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰew-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bu-||to swell}}<ref>{{R:ine:IEW|98-102}}</ref> (compare {{cog|no|bugge||big man}}, dialectal Low German {{m|nds|Bögge||goblin”, “snot}}). Or, from a word related to {{m|en|buck}} and originally referring to a goat-shaped specter.
# {{der|en|enm|budde||beetle}}, from {{der|en|ang|budda}} (see {{m|ang|sċearnbudda||dung beetle}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*buddô}}, {{m|gem-pro|*buzdô}}, from the same ultimate source as above (compare {{cog|nds|Budde||louse, grub}}, {{cog|no|budda||newborn domestic animal}}). More at {{l|en|bud}}.
The term is used to refer to technical errors and problems at least as early as the 19th century, predating the commonly known story of a moth being caught in a computer.

